ð¾ The Data

In this project, I gathered data about the top 2000 universities worldwide through 3 steps:

  • Web Scraping the top 2000 universities from CWUR rankings
  • Obtaining more information from APIs in Wikipedia
  • Scraping additional information from the Wikipedia Webpage, fetching additional data.

I then preprocessed the information and discarded columns that were irrelevant to the analysis (e.g html links, reference page numbersâ¦).

-> One significant process I faced was handling inconsistencies in university names and formatting variations between different sources. I used string manipulation and replacement functions to ensure uniformity.

Here are four plots meant to provide a bigger picture of the dataset. Note that there is a function that takes the path as an argument for all these 4 plots.

The distribution of top universities is very unequal in the world. Reasons for this could be population variations or country development.

3. Temporal Dimension of the Data

It is also interesting to look at when these top universities were established.

expand for full code 
source("R/data_viz.R")

Interestingly, most of these universities have been founded in the last two decades. Industrial revolutions and the baby boom might be causes that led to this: more means to develop and more people to educate.

4. Mean Ranking by Number of Students

We are using the number of student here to see how many are in the university depending on the ranking.

expand for full code 
source("R/data_viz.R")
plot_mean_ranking_by_students("data/tidy/tidy_dataset.csv")

Unsurprisingly, the more the number of students is high, the least the mean ranking will be. This can mean that a university with a higher ranking has more resources to provide to its students.

ð Further Exploratory Analysis

Below are three plots meant to give a further understanding of the dataset and its intricacies. It is worth noting that for each of these 3 plots, a function has been made and takes the path of the document as an argument.

1. Number of Students in Type of University

It might be interesting to explore the number of students in each type of university.

expand for full code 
source("R/data_viz.R")
plot_students_by_university_type("data/tidy/tidy_dataset.csv")

Public universities account for a larger share of students compared to private universities, which could indicate that public universities are more prevalent to students in the dataset. The reasons for this observation could vary and might be influenced by factors such as:

  • Funding from the government, making the facilities of a higher quality
  • Affordability of the university, enabling the student to attend
  • Less selective admission policies

2. Trends of University Types by Ranking Range

In our purpose of exploring the trends in university types further, we are going to display the percentage of each university type across different ranking ranges.

expand for full code 
source("R/data_viz.R")
plot_university_types_by_ranking("data/tidy/tidy_dataset.csv")

This plot reveals interesting trends:

  • while public university make up the majority of the top 2000 universities, private universities seem to be relatively numerous in the top 100 rankings (>25%), but their percentage significantly drops in the ranking range 101-300. It rises back again in the range 301-400 and overall increases until the range 901-1000, after which it fluctuates.

The numerous private universities in the top 100 suggests that a number of private universities have achieved high rankings and are recognized for their academic excellence. With that said, we can see that as the ranking range expands beyond the top 100, there is a significant drop in their number. Many factors could explain this: - Public universities often have larger budget and funding, which puts them at an advantage in terms of research opportunities, infrastructure, and faculty resources - Public universities, especially those with state funding, might offer more affordable tuition rates, making them more accessible

  • The increase in private universities after the 301-400 range highlights the competitive and emerging market of private universities.It is difficult for new universities to obtain the same level of funding and establishment old universities obtain, which might explain why more private universities are competing in the higher ranking ranges.

  • There is a steady increase in missing values (NA) as the ranking range increases. Letâs further analyze this trend and consider potential reasons behind it:

  • As the ranking range expands, it is possible that some universities might not provide complete data or fail to report specific information required for calculations.

  • Certain universities, especially those with lower rankings, may choose not to participate in the ranking surveys if they believe their rankings might not be favourable

3. Type of university depending on location

It would be interesting to see how the percentage of type of university varies across locations.

expand for full code 
source("R/data_viz.R")
plot_private_universities_map("data/tidy/tidy_dataset.csv")

Note that countries in gray do not have any university described as private in the top 2000.

We see that in most countries, except the USA, the vast majority of universities are public.

The USA stands out as an outlier in terms of having a substantial percentage of private universities compared to most other countries. This is likely due to the countryâs unique higher education system, where private universities can sometimes provide more financial aid than public universities, and the offerings some private universities provide over public universities.

Note that all plots are stored in âdata/plotsâ

Conclusion of this research study and plots we explored

In conclusion, the analysis of the top 2000 universities worldwide reveals significant insights into the global landscape of higher education:

  • The distribution of universities by country highlights pronounced disparities, with some regions having a higher concentration of top-ranked institutions
  • Public universities dominate the dataset, but private universities show a notable presence in the top 100 rankings
  • There is a surge in university establishments in the last two decades, possibly driven by socio-economic factors
  • Universities with larger student bodies tend to have lower mean rankings

The prevalence of public universities in most countries and the rise of private universities in certain ranking ranges prompt further exploration into funding, accessibility, and educational policies.

â­ï¸ Future

If I had more time to work in this project, I would:

  • investigate in way more depth the data depending on each country. All nations have different policies when it comes to university. For instance, China mostly has public universities with some niche exceptions, as opposed to the US where there are a lot of private universities.

  • collect more data. For instance, the acceptance rate for each university or its endowment would have been valuable to explore.

  • use more rankings: indeed, I only used the CWUR ranking source which can lead to a biased ranking that only accounts for specific metrics.

  • create dataframes by subject: the ranking used was global and did not delve into the fields of study for each university. If I had more time, it would also be an area I would explore.

One practice that helped me throughout this process and that I plan on keeping in the future is brainstorm on a piece of paper to gather ideas on the plots I could make. This was very useful for me and I am happy it led to me producing these 7 plots!
